      <span class="faq-arrow">&#9654;</span>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <p>Torsion springs are mounted on a rod above the garage door opening and twist to lift the door. They're safer, last longer (10,000-20,000 cycles), and are standard on most modern garage doors. Extension springs run along the sides of the door and stretch to provide lift. They're more common on older doors, have a shorter lifespan (10,000 cycles), and are more dangerous when they break. If you have extension springs and they're breaking frequently, we can often upgrade you to torsion springs for better performance and safety.</p>
    </div>
